@node Storing Org links for commits and topics
@section Storing Org links for commits and topics

@findex forge-extras-orgit-store-link
A common workflow when writing notes or documentation is to link back to
specific commits or forge topics.  The command
@code{forge-extras-orgit-store-link} extends the standard @code{org-store-link} to
handle two Magit/Forge contexts:

@itemize
@item
When multiple commit sections are selected in a Magit log or status
buffer (via the region), it iterates through each selected commit and
stores an Org link for every one of them.  This is useful when you
want to reference a range of commits without invoking @code{org-store-link}
repeatedly.

@item
When there is no active region of commit sections, the command
determines whether point is on a pull request or an issue.  It visits
the corresponding topic buffer and stores a link from there, so you
get a properly formatted orgit link even when invoked from the topic
list.
@end itemize

@node Browsing the GitHub notification inbox
@section Browsing the GitHub notification inbox

@findex forge-extras-browse-github-inbox
The command @code{forge-extras-browse-github-inbox} opens the GitHub
notifications page in your default browser.  It is a thin wrapper around
@code{browse-url} and is handy as a quick escape hatch when you want to
triage notifications in the web interface rather than in Forge.

@node Toggling issue or pull request state
@section Toggling issue or pull request state

@findex forge-extras-state-set-dwim
The command @code{forge-extras-state-set-dwim} provides a single key binding
that toggles the state of the current topic: if the issue or pull
request is open, it closes it (setting the state to @code{completed}); if it
is already completed, it reopens it (setting the state to @code{open}).

The command operates on the topic at point or, if none is found, the
topic associated with the current buffer.  You can also pass an ISSUE
argument programmatically.

@node Pulling notifications
@section Pulling notifications

@findex forge-extras-pull-notifications
The command @code{forge-extras-pull-notifications} calls
@code{forge-pull-notifications} silently, suppressing all output via
@samp{shut-up} and @samp{with-no-warnings}.  It also guards against running when
an Elfeed update is in progress (detected via
@code{elfeed-extras-auto-update-in-process}), because concurrent database
access was found to cause problems.

This command is primarily intended for use in timers or hooks (for
example, to refresh notifications periodically in the background) rather
than direct interactive invocation.

@node Notification and read-status synchronization
@section Notification and read-status synchronization

@findex forge-extras-sync-read-status
When you visit a topic in Forge, GitHub may still show it as unread
because Forge only updates local notification state, not GitHub's.  The
function @code{forge-extras-sync-read-status} bridges this gap by calling the
GitHub REST API (@code{PATCH /notifications/threads/@{thread-id@}}) to mark
the notification thread as read.

The function only acts when the topic at point has an @code{unread} status in
Forge.  It looks up the corresponding @code{forge-notification} object to
obtain the GitHub thread ID, then issues the API call asynchronously
via @code{forge--rest}.  On success, it refreshes the notification count in
Doom Modeline (if @code{doom-modeline-github} is enabled).

@findex forge-extras-sync-unread-from-github
The complementary function @code{forge-extras-sync-unread-from-github}
handles the reverse direction: it ensures that notifications marked as
unread on GitHub's web interface are also shown as unread in Forge.
This is needed because marking a notification as unread on GitHub does
not update its @code{updated_at} timestamp, so Forge's incremental pull
(which uses a @code{since} filter based on that timestamp) skips those
notifications entirely.

The function is installed as @code{:after} advice on
@code{forge--ghub-update-notifications}, so it runs automatically at the end
of every @code{forge-pull-notifications} call.  It queries the GitHub REST
API for currently-unread notifications via the @samp{gh} CLI, then sets the
local topic status to @code{unread} for any that Forge missed.

@node Tracking repositories
@section Tracking repositories

@findex forge-extras-track-repository
When you clone a new repository or want Forge to know about one that
predates your Forge setup, the command @code{forge-extras-track-repository}
adds a directory's Git repository to the Forge database.  It accepts an
optional DIR argument (defaulting to @code{default-directory}), verifies that
the directory is a Git repository (using @code{vc-extras-is-git-dir-p} from
@samp{vc-extras.el}), retrieves the remote URL, inserts the repository into
the Forge database with @code{forge-get-repository} using the @samp{:insert!}
keyword, pulls all topics via @code{forge--pull}, and opens a Magit status
buffer for the directory.

If you have a URL or local path rather than a directory with an
existing checkout, the supporting function
@code{forge-extras-track-repo-all-topics} handles the lower-level logic of
resolving URLs and pulling topics.

@node Navigating messages in a topic buffer
@section Navigating messages in a topic buffer

@findex forge-next-message
@findex forge-previous-message
When reading a long discussion thread in a Forge topic buffer, it is
convenient to jump between posts without scrolling.  The command
@code{forge-next-message} moves point to the start of the next post section,
and @code{forge-previous-message} moves to the previous one.

If point is not currently on a post section, @code{forge-next-message} jumps
to the first post and @code{forge-previous-message} jumps to the last.  When
there is no further post in the requested direction, a message is
displayed in the echo area.

Both commands delegate to the internal function @code{forge--goto-message},
which navigates by inspecting Magit section siblings of type @code{post}.

@node Copying a message body
@section Copying a message body

@findex forge-extras-copy-message-at-point-as-kill
The command @code{forge-extras-copy-message-at-point-as-kill} copies the body
of the Forge post at point to the kill ring, preserving its original
formatting.  This is useful when you want to quote or reuse a comment
from a GitHub discussion in another context, such as an email or an Org
document.

@node Inserting Markdown links to GitHub issues
@section Inserting Markdown links to GitHub issues

@findex forge-extras-insert-issue-markdown-link
The command @code{forge-extras-insert-issue-markdown-link} fetches issues from
one or more GitHub repositories, presents them in a completing-read
prompt, and inserts a Markdown-formatted link at point.  This is
particularly useful when writing commit messages, pull request
descriptions, or documentation that needs to reference specific issues.

When called interactively, the command prompts for repositories as a
space- or comma-separated list of @samp{"owner/repo"} strings.  It then calls
the @samp{gh} CLI to fetch issues whose state matches
@code{forge-extras-issue-link-state} (@ref{Issue link state}),
up to 300 per repository.

The completion candidates are displayed as @samp{"owner/repo #NUMBER: TITLE"},
sorted by repository name (ascending) and then by issue number
(descending, so the most recent issues appear first within each
repository).  Upon selection, a Markdown link of the form
@samp{[owner/repo#NUMBER](URL)} is inserted at point.

@findex forge-extras-test-fetch-issues
The companion command @code{forge-extras-test-fetch-issues} is a debugging
aid.  It fetches issues for a single repository and echoes the count,
helping you verify that the @samp{gh} CLI is authenticated and working.

@node GitHub Project integration
@chapter GitHub Project integration

The GitHub Projects v2 features in @samp{forge-extras.el} let you manage
project board metadata---status, estimates, and item listings---directly
from Emacs.  All of these commands communicate with the GitHub GraphQL
API by shelling out to the @samp{gh} CLI, which must be installed and
authenticated.

@menu
* Setting up GitHub Project integration::
* Setting project status::
* Setting project estimates::
* Discovering project IDs::
* Listing project items::
@end menu

@node Setting up GitHub Project integration
@section Setting up GitHub Project integration

Before you can use any of the project commands, several user options need
to be configured.  The process involves discovering various Node IDs from
GitHub's GraphQL API:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Set the project owner and number.}  Configure
@code{forge-extras-project-owner} (@ref{Project owner and number})
with the organization or user name, and @code{forge-extras-project-number}
with the integer from the project URL@.

@item
@strong{Obtain the project Node ID@.}  Use the @samp{gh} CLI:
@example
# For an organization-owned project:
gh api graphql -f query='query@{organization(login:"YOUR_ORG")@{projectV2(number:NUMBER)@{id@}@}@}'

# For a user-owned project:
gh api graphql -f query='query@{user(login:"YOUR_USER")@{projectV2(number:NUMBER)@{id@}@}@}'
@end example
Set @code{forge-extras-project-node-id} (@ref{Project Node ID})
to the returned ID string.

@item
@strong{Discover field Node IDs.}  Run @samp{M-x forge-extras-get-project-field-ids}
(@ref{Getting project field IDs}).
From the resulting buffer, copy the Node IDs for the ``Status'' and
``Estimate'' fields into @code{forge-extras-status-field-node-id}
(@ref{Status field Node ID}) and
@code{forge-extras-estimate-field-node-id}
(@ref{Estimate field Node ID}).

@item
@strong{Discover status option IDs.}  Run @samp{M-x forge-extras-discover-project-status-options}
(@ref{Discovering status options}).
The output buffer contains an alist ready for insertion into your
configuration as the value of @code{forge-extras-status-option-ids-alist}
(@ref{Status option IDs alist}).
@end enumerate

@node Setting project status
@section Setting project status

@findex forge-extras-set-project-status
The command @code{forge-extras-set-project-status} sets the ``Status''
single-select field for the current topic within the configured GitHub
Project.  When called interactively, it defaults ISSUE to
@code{forge-current-topic} and prompts for a status from the keys of
@code{forge-extras-status-option-ids-alist}
(@ref{Status option IDs alist}).  The current
project status of the issue is offered as the default in the prompt.

If the issue is not yet a member of the target project, the command
automatically adds it before setting the status.  After a successful
update, if you are in a @code{forge-topic-mode} buffer, the buffer is
refreshed to reflect the change.

You can also call this command programmatically with explicit ISSUE and
STATUS arguments, bypassing the prompt.

@node Setting project estimates
@section Setting project estimates

@findex forge-extras-set-project-estimate
The command @code{forge-extras-set-project-estimate} sets a numeric estimate
(story points, hours, or whatever your project uses) for the current
topic within the configured GitHub Project.  It reads the current
estimate from the project data and offers it as the default when
prompting.

Like @code{forge-extras-set-project-status}
(@ref{Setting project status}), this command
automatically adds the issue to the project if it is not already present.
It requires @code{forge-extras-estimate-field-node-id}
(@ref{Estimate field Node ID}) to be configured.

